= $ section$ 1.1 : What is Dynamical Systems

Note: Dynamical systems is the maths of behavior and the classification of how systems change over time. (ex: pendulums affected by an outside force). Dynamical systems are used to predict future states of systems as well, and dynamical systems are used to model physical systems. \ 

= $ section$ 1.2 : Continuous & Discrete Time

Note: In a dynamical system a large deliniator of  systems is whether time is continuous or discrete. 
Note: Continous time means $t in RR ^+ "or" RR$, and Discrete time means $t in NN "or" ZZ$ 
= $section$ 1.3 : State Space

Note: All changes of a system occur in a state space.
Def: State Space - A space containing all possible states of a system.
Ex: The velocity of a falling object w/ drag would be $ X = (-infinity, 0]$ as the object is falling, so the velocity is constrainted to non-positive real numbers.
Note: This volume deals primarily with $RR ^1$ (line) and $SS ^1$ (circle) state spaces.
= $ section$ 1.4 : Qualitative vs Quantitative

Note: Qualitative explainations are often more useful than a closed form quantitative solution for some dynamical systems.

= $section$ 1.5 : Equilibria & Stability

Def: Equilibrium - A constant solution that remains fixed as time changes. 
Note: System dynamics evolve about equilibria. 
Def: Stable (Equilibrium) - An equilibrium that the system evolves towards.
Def: Unstable (Equilibrium) - An equilibrium that systems evolve away from.

= $section$ 1.6 : Parameters & Bifurcations

Def: Parameters - Constants that can be changed in a system to change the dynamics of a system. 
Def: Bifurcation - Locations in state & parameter space where there is a local change in the number or types of equilibria present. 

= $section$ 1.7 : Periodic Phenomena & Chaos 

Def: Periodic orbits / cycles - Repeated behavior in a system. 
Note: Chaos describes unpredictable behavior of systems over longer periods of time.

